":[{"name":"Walles","meanings":["English: variant of   Wallace  ."]},{"name":"Wallis","meanings":["Scottish and English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>Waleis</i>, <i>Walais</i> ‘Welshman’, also sometimes ‘Breton’ (from Old English <i>wēalas</i>, <i>walas</i>, plural of <i>walh</i>, <i>wealh</i>, originally meaning a ‘Roman citizen’ and referring to the native British population, but in Old English this term later came to mean ‘serf, unfree person, foreigner’ or ‘Welshman’). In western and central England the medieval reference is clearly to Welshmen. In Norfolk and Lincolnshire, the reference was probably to Bretons, many of whom settled in the eastern counties after the Conquest. Compare   Welsh  ,   Walsh  . The idea that the Scottish surname refers to the Welsh-speaking Britons of Strathclyde is erroneous."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Wallace 10th of Riccarton was born in 1390, in Craigie, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, William Wallace 9th of Riccarton, was 13 and his mother, Elizabeth Douglas, was 15. He married Elizabeth de Cathcart in 1415, in Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in January 1450, in Riccarton, Ayrshire, Scotland, at the age of 60, and was buried in Riccarton, Ayrshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1390–January 1450":"1390–jaanuar 1450","1390–1450":"1390–1450","1395–1424":"1395–1424","1415–1472":"1415–1472","1377–Male":"1377–Surnud","1375–1458":"1375–1458","1415":"1415","1458":"1458","1424":"1424","17 August 1424":"17. august 1424","1377":"1377","5 January 1415":"5. jaanuar 1415","January 1450":"jaanuar 1450","1375":"1375","1450":